Book II. contains the narrative already given of the wooden horse, the sack of Troy, and the hair-breadth escape of Aeneas with the loss of his wife Creusa 3 and the tale continues in Book III., wherein are described the various fruitless attempts of the fugitives to settle in Thrace, Epirus, and Sicily, and the death of Anchises.

Book IV. contains the story of Dido's passion for Aeneas, his marriage with her, and his speedy departure at the bidding of the gods, who refused to allow him to settle elsewhere than in Italy. In despair the queen commits suicide.

In Book V. we have a long description of the games celebrated at Eryx in Sicily, the colony of AcesteS, another Trojan refugee, in honour of the dead Anchises. The boat race, foot racc, boxing, wrestling, and shooting matches are all described in detail, and the book closes with the ultimate arrival of Aeneas in Italy.

He meets also his father Anchises, who unfolds 10 him all the future glory of Rome. The book thus becomes a magnificent prophecy, foretelling the wars and triumphs of Rome up to Actium, B.o. 31.
